Text Normalization¶

  1. Lower Case
  2. Removing punctuation and numbers
  3. Tokenisation of the transcription
  4. Lemmatisation or Stemming
  5. Remove Stop Words

1. Lower Case¶

In [6]:
def lower(df, attribute):
    df.loc[:,attribute] = df[attribute].apply(lambda x : str.lower(str(x)))
    return df
dfs = lower(dfs,'transcription')

def remove_punc_num(df, attribute):
    df.loc[:,attribute] = df[attribute].apply(lambda x : " ".join(re.findall('[\w]+',str(x))))
    df[attribute] = df[attribute].str.replace('\d+', '')
    return df
dfs =remove_punc_num(dfs, 'transcription').copy(deep=True)

In [8]:
tk =WhitespaceTokenizer()
def tokenise(df, attribute):
    df['tokenised'] = df.apply(lambda row: tk.tokenize(str(row[attribute])), axis=1)
    return df

4. Stemming¶

In [9]:
from nltk.stem.snowball import SnowballStemmer
def stemming(df, attribute):
    # Use English stemmer.
    stemmer = SnowballStemmer("english")
    df['stemmed'] = df[attribute].apply(lambda x: [stemmer.stem(y) for y in x]) # Stem every word.
    return df
dfs =stemming(dfs, 'tokenised').copy(deep=True)
dfs.head(5)

# Removing stop words
def remove_stop_words(df, attribute):
    stop = stopwords.words('english')
    df['stemmed_without_stop'] = df[attribute].apply(lambda x: ' '.join([word for word in x if word not in (stop)]))
    return df
dfs = remove_stop_words(dfs, 'stemmed').copy(deep=True)
dfs.head(5)

Logistic Regression for Classifying into Medical Specialty from Transcription¶

  1. We will use complete set to create vocab and vectors
  2. Check frequency of each word in each of the class and create frequency table
  3. For for each trascription create a vector using frequency table
  4. Train logistic regression on a subset, train set
  5. Test the model prediction on test set
Creating freqency table (here in form of Counter/dictionary)¶
In [26]:
cardio_words_lst = cardio_words.split(" ")
gastro_words_lst = gastro_words.split(" ")
cardio_dict_counter = Counter(cardio_words_lst)
gastro_dict_counter = Counter(gastro_words_lst)
Creating features using frequency table¶
In [36]:
dfs['Cardio Freq'] = 0
dfs['Gastro Freq'] = 0
dfs['Class'] = 0
for i in range(len(dfs)):
    cardio_count = 0
    gastro_count = 0
    word_lst = dfs.loc[i,'stemmed_without_stop'].split(" ")
    if(dfs.loc[i,'medical_specialty']==' Cardiovascular / Pulmonary'):
        dfs.loc[i,'Class']=0
    else:
        dfs.loc[i,'Class']=1
    for w in word_lst:
        cardio_count+=cardio_dict_counter[w]
        gastro_count+=gastro_dict_counter[w]
    dfs.loc[i,'Cardio Freq'] = cardio_count
    dfs.loc[i,'Gastro Freq'] = gastro_count

Splitting data into train and test¶
In [51]:
X_train = np.reshape(train_df[['Cardio Freq','Gastro Freq']].values,(-1,2))
Y_train = train_df.Class.values
X_test = np.reshape(test_df[['Cardio Freq','Gastro Freq']].values,(-1,2))
Y_test = test_df.Class.values
Training a Logistic Regression Model¶
In [54]:
clf = LogisticRegression(solver='lbfgs',random_state=0).fit(X_train,Y_train)
a = clf.coef_[0]
b = clf.intercept_[0]
print(a,b)
